WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:17.580
&gt;&gt; Karen Lloyd: Good afternoon.

00:00:17.580 --> 00:00:20.760
I'm Karen Lloyd, Director of
the Veterans History Project.

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:24.090
And it is my pleasure to welcome
you to the Library of Congress

00:00:24.090 --> 00:00:26.390
and our behind the
mic panel discussion

00:00:26.390 --> 00:00:28.850
to examine the interviewer's
role

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:31.360
and experience with
oral history.

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:34.460
Oral history is a principal
conduit for folklore.

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:37.360
It is through oral history
that we're able to learn

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:41.450
about the life experiences and
perspectives of individuals

00:00:41.450 --> 00:00:45.470
who might not otherwise
appear in historical records.

00:00:45.470 --> 00:00:49.170
Recorded interviews provide
uniqueness to the qualities

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:54.160
of human voice that is its
expression like inflections,

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:57.690
hesitation, dialect
and emotional range.

00:00:57.690 --> 00:01:01.070
The content of these
interviews also provide a rich

00:01:01.070 --> 00:01:03.420
human interaction.

00:01:03.420 --> 00:01:06.290
As I watch and listen to
the stories in our archive,

00:01:06.290 --> 00:01:09.440
as well as meet the veterans and
their loved ones face-to-face,

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:11.550
I am more and more grateful

00:01:11.550 --> 00:01:15.050
for our veterans'
service and sacrifice.

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:16.990
I am thankful that
Congress understood

00:01:16.990 --> 00:01:19.730
that oral history
aspect of folklore

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:24.480
when it established the Veterans
History Project in year 2000.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:27.420
Congress established
VHP as a project

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:30.630
within the American Folklife
Center of the Library

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:34.420
of Congress, because it was seen
as an appropriate repository

00:01:34.420 --> 00:01:36.950
to collect, preserve,
and make available

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:40.030
to the public an archive
of oral histories.

00:01:40.030 --> 00:01:44.240
In two days, we will celebrate
our 17th anniversary and I am

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:48.050
so proud to report that
we currently hold more

00:01:48.050 --> 00:01:52.720
than 104,000 collections
of selfless service

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:57.600
of our brave men and women
who served in the US military

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:00.680
from World War I through
the current conflicts.

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.050
It would have been
impossible for our staff

00:02:03.050 --> 00:02:06.910
to archive this much history
without the direct involvement

00:02:06.910 --> 00:02:11.830
of organizations like Witness to
War, Vietnam War Commemoration,

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:14.360
Members of Congress
and volunteers

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.730
from across the country,
who interviewed veterans

00:02:17.730 --> 00:02:20.800
in their lives and
in their communities.

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:22.350
In addition to the interviews,

00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:26.070
they also donate other
historic materials

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:30.700
such as original photographs,
letters, diaries, journals,

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:34.640
two-dimensional artwork and
official military documents,

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:37.420
at a rate of about
a hundred per week.

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:39.970
The Veterans History
Project engages veterans

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:43.210
from every branch of
service and their loved ones

00:02:43.210 --> 00:02:47.230
and our content is used
by researchers, educators,

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:52.340
students, authors, filmmakers,
and the general public.

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:55.420
We are deeply honored to
host this panel where we get

00:02:55.420 --> 00:02:57.420
to take a peek behind
the curtain

00:02:57.420 --> 00:02:59.900
of the interviewer experience.

00:02:59.900 --> 00:03:02.090
It is now my pleasure
to introduce

00:03:02.090 --> 00:03:05.010
to you our distinguished panel.

00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:10.080
I'd like to start with Joe
Galloway, a native Texan.

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:12.880
Joe joined the United
Press International

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:15.680
as a reporter in 1961.

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:18.920
During his 22 years with UPI,

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:22.190
Joe served in nearly
a dozen news bureaus

00:03:22.190 --> 00:03:26.070
in the American Midwest
and also Asia.

00:03:26.070 --> 00:03:28.610
Joe began a 16-month
tour of Vietnam

00:03:28.610 --> 00:03:33.050
as a war correspondent
beginning in April 1965,

00:03:33.050 --> 00:03:36.310
shortly after the first
American combat troops arrived

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:37.960
in Vietnam.

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:43.710
He did three other tours in
Vietnam, one in 1971, one in '73

00:03:43.710 --> 00:03:49.350
and his last in 1975
covering the fall of Saigon.

00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:53.070
Joe spent 20 years as a senior
editor and senior writer

00:03:53.070 --> 00:03:56.150
for the US News &amp;
World Report magazine

00:03:56.150 --> 00:04:00.100
and just recently retired as a
senior military correspondent

00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:02.270
for Knight Ridder newspapers.

00:04:02.270 --> 00:04:05.640
Joe served as special consultant
to General Colin Powell

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:07.060
at the State Department.

00:04:07.060 --> 00:04:11.400
That had been amazing and
co-authored several books.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.060
He is most often
recognized as the co-author

00:04:14.060 --> 00:04:17.300
of the national bestselling
book, "We Were Soldiers Once...

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:20.460
and Young" with General
Hal Moore.

00:04:20.460 --> 00:04:26.140
The book was later turned
into a feature film in 2002,

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:28.540
starring Mel Gibson
as General Moore.

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:32.300
More recently, Joe has been
portrayed by Tommy Lee Jones

00:04:32.300 --> 00:04:36.130
in a film "Shock and Awe", a
reflection of his reputation

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:38.470
for journalistic integrity.

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:41.060
He has received numerous
awards for his writing,

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:42.840
but I think he would tell you,

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:46.610
his most significant
recognition came in 1998,

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:48.960
when the army awarded
him a bronze star

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:55.440
for rescuing a wounded soldier
under fire in November 1965.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:58.960
This was the only such medal
for valor awarded to a civilian

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:01.830
by the army for actions
undertaken during the

00:05:01.830 --> 00:05:03.160
Vietnam War.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:08.300
Next, we have Emily Carley with
the Witness to War Foundation.

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:13.740
Thank you Emily, a nonprofit
501c3 founded in 2001

00:05:13.740 --> 00:05:16.090
and dedicated to
capturing the stories

00:05:16.090 --> 00:05:19.190
of individual combat
veterans, honoring them

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:23.070
and educating future generations
about the price of freedom

00:05:23.070 --> 00:05:26.270
and extraordinary valor
for our forbearers.

00:05:26.270 --> 00:05:29.920
The Witness to War Foundation
is dedicated to understanding

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.770
as much as possible, what
it was like to be there.

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:38.370
Emily is an Atlanta native and a
2006 graduate of the University

00:05:38.370 --> 00:05:42.010
of Tennessee with a
BA/BS in Marketing.

00:05:42.010 --> 00:05:45.460
Her grandfather was a World
War II and Korean War veteran

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:49.490
and is featured on the
Witness to War website.

00:05:49.490 --> 00:05:52.470
He is Tank Commander Andrew
Carpenter, in case you're going

00:05:52.470 --> 00:05:54.370
to check it out later.

00:05:54.370 --> 00:05:57.050
Emily originally
assisted with interviewing

00:05:57.050 --> 00:06:00.290
and website content
selection prior to moving

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:02.090
into the director position.

00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:05.760
Emily has been working with
the foundation since 2006,

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:09.100
where today she is responsible
for the day-to-day running

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:12.790
of the Foundation including
partnership and media contacts

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:15.190
and website management.

00:06:15.190 --> 00:06:19.600
Next to Emily is Guha
Shankar, a folklife specialist

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:21.730
at the American Folklife Center.

00:06:21.730 --> 00:06:23.340
Guha is involved in a range

00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:26.910
of public outreach programs
including the Civil Rights

00:06:26.910 --> 00:06:30.850
Project, a national
initiative to conduct surveys

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:34.120
of existing oral history
collections with relevance

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:37.450
to the Civil Rights Movements
and to record new interviews

00:06:37.450 --> 00:06:40.340
with people who participated
in the movement.

00:06:40.340 --> 00:06:41.640
The recollections

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:44.740
of interviewees cover a
wide variety of topics

00:06:44.740 --> 00:06:47.520
about the freedom struggle
such as the Influence

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:50.750
of Organized Labor,
Nonviolence and Self Defense,

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:55.190
and the Importance of Faith,
Music, Family and Friendships,

00:06:55.190 --> 00:06:58.900
and that last piece as a veteran
really resonates with me.

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:01.780
Like many of our veterans,
the individuals involved

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:04.200
in Civil Rights Movement
fought bravely

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:05.780
for what they believed in.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:08.910
They often experienced
intense traumatic events

00:07:08.910 --> 00:07:11.500
that have ultimately
defined their life.

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:15.490
Their actions and moments
in time are meaningful,

00:07:15.490 --> 00:07:19.660
not just to the individuals,
but also for larger history.

00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:23.400
Events discussed in these
interviews include the murder

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:29.260
of 14-year-old Emmett Till in
1955, the Freedom Rights in '61,

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:32.920
the March on Washington for
Jobs and Freedom in '63,

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:36.580
the Selma to Montgomery
Rights March in '65.

00:07:36.580 --> 00:07:39.680
The 130 plus interviews
are a permanent part

00:07:39.680 --> 00:07:43.410
of the recently opened
national museum.

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:48.000
Guha earned his PhD in 2003 from
the Department of Anthropology,

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.530
University of Texas Austin
with the concentration

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:53.800
in folklore and public culture.

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:56.080
Prior to undertaking
his graduate studies,

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:58.260
he was a media production
specialist

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:02.810
and documentary film producer at
the Center for Folklife Programs

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:06.050
at the Smithsonian Institution's
Center for Folklife

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:07.830
and Cultural Heritage.

00:08:07.830 --> 00:08:10.110
As an army colonel,
I am thrilled

00:08:10.110 --> 00:08:15.790
to welcome our next panel
member and my compatriot, Mark--

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:17.910
Colonel Mark Franklin.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:20.910
Through Colonel Franklin
served 30 years of service,

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:22.730
he held a variety of positions,

00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:25.920
starting as a weapons
platoon leader and culminating

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:30.280
as a political military adviser
as the Okinawa area coordinator

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:32.640
and senior country
director in the China,

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:36.500
Asia and Pacific Securities
Office under Secretary

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:39.910
of Defense for policy,
where he was responsible

00:08:39.910 --> 00:08:43.250
for developing military

00:08:43.250 --> 00:08:47.090
to military relationship
with China.

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:51.150
Mark currently serves as the
chief history and legacy branch

00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:54.050
for the Vietnam War
Commemoration.

00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:58.230
Vietnam War Commemoration
was created in 2008 by act

00:08:58.230 --> 00:09:03.200
of Congress and will last
until Veterans Day 2025.

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:06.950
The mission of the commemoration
is to assist our nation

00:09:06.950 --> 00:09:11.050
in thanking and honoring Vietnam
veterans, their families,

00:09:11.050 --> 00:09:14.900
the fallen, those who are
held prisoner of war and those

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:17.550
that are still unaccounted for.

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:19.490
In support of that
mission, the history

00:09:19.490 --> 00:09:23.180
and legacy branch strives to
provide the American public

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:26.910
with a clear understanding and
appreciation of the service,

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:29.710
sacrifice of our veterans
and ensure the legacy

00:09:29.710 --> 00:09:33.930
of their service endures
for future generations.

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:36.200
Lastly, our moderator,
thank you Andrew.

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:40.550
Last but not least,
is Dr. Andrew Ringlee,

00:09:40.550 --> 00:09:44.850
Dr. Ringlee is a historian for
the Vietnam War Commemoration.

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:48.090
He received his PhD in
History from the University

00:09:48.090 --> 00:09:51.980
of North Carolina at
Chapel Hill in 2016.

00:09:51.980 --> 00:09:54.910
He works on the Vietnam War
Commemorations Oral History

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:57.900
Project, conducting
interviews in Washington,

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:00.160
DC and several other cities.

00:10:00.160 --> 00:10:03.470
Andrew received numerous
academic awards including a

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:07.240
Fulbright-Hays to conduct
dissertation research

00:10:07.240 --> 00:10:10.150
in Russia in 2013.

00:10:10.150 --> 00:10:12.190
I will now turn the
microphone over to Andrew

00:10:12.190 --> 00:10:15.280
who will explain the
format of today's panel.

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:17.580
Thank you, Andrew.

00:10:23.730 --> 00:10:26.140
&gt;&gt; Andrew Ringlee: I would
like to thank Karen Lloyd

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:28.600
for that warm introduction
and for hosting us here

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:30.730
and I also want to thank
Kerry Ward for her help

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:34.550
in bringing this
panel into being.

00:10:34.550 --> 00:10:36.000
First of all, I will-- I answer

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.390
or ask the panelists several
questions, both panels,

00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:43.500
general questions the entire
panel and a couple specific

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:45.050
to individuals on the panel.

00:10:45.050 --> 00:10:47.850
Then afterwards, I would
like to open the discussion

00:10:47.850 --> 00:10:51.350
to the audience and I would
encourage you to ask questions

00:10:51.350 --> 00:10:54.340
for panelist either
for the entire panel

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:58.240
or for individuals on the panel.

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:01.280
Oral history is important for
its critical ability to fill

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:05.850
in the gaps in our historical
records, enables us to capture

00:11:05.850 --> 00:11:08.260
and preserve accounts that
we would otherwise lose,

00:11:08.260 --> 00:11:12.730
be they subaltern voices or even
people who are very important

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:18.530
who choose not to commit their
thoughts to written prose.

00:11:18.530 --> 00:11:22.310
In introduction question for
everyone on these panelists,

00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:26.300
can you describe a moment when
you realize in an interview

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:31.420
that what the interviewee
was saying had changed your

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:35.550
understanding of an
historical event or process?

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:38.160
And perhaps we can
start with Guha.

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:40.730
&gt;&gt; Guha Shankar: Thanks.

00:11:40.730 --> 00:11:46.000
I think I go back to one of
the very first interviews

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:47.750
that I was a part of
here at the Library.

00:11:47.750 --> 00:11:49.990
I've done several on my own.

00:11:49.990 --> 00:11:52.960
But I was acting as a sound
recorder for an interview

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:54.300
that we did during the opening

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:56.950
of the World War II
Memorial here in the mall

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:58.910
and memory escapes me.

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:00.480
It was at least-- it
was a long time ago.

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:03.710
It was about at least 10
years ago if I'm not mistaken.

00:12:03.710 --> 00:12:06.730
And one of the people whom
we were interviewing was this

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:08.820
elderly gentleman who
had been brought here

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:12.070
by his congressman
from Michigan.

00:12:12.070 --> 00:12:14.730
And at the course of the
interview, I want to cut

00:12:14.730 --> 00:12:18.710
to the point, he had never, as
I found out, as I was talking

00:12:18.710 --> 00:12:23.620
to his two adult daughters,
they said, "He has never talked

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:26.770
about his war experiences
to us ever."

00:12:26.770 --> 00:12:29.620
And so for them it was a
moment to listen and understand

00:12:29.620 --> 00:12:33.720
from their father's own words
what his experiences were.

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:37.500
And at the course of the
interview, he starts talking

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:40.220
about essentially being
transported at the end

00:12:40.220 --> 00:12:43.570
of the war having been
shot down, 19-year-old,

00:12:43.570 --> 00:12:49.490
sent across the border
and into Germany,

00:12:49.490 --> 00:12:52.700
somewhere in the
Polish border, I think.

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:57.480
And he says at that moment, and
this is a capstone argument,

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:02.780
he says, "I didn't realize until
they told me where we were going

00:13:02.780 --> 00:13:07.730
to be barracked, that it was the
birthplace of my grandparents.

00:13:07.730 --> 00:13:09.980
And yes, I heard the, ahh.

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:11.280
[laughter] I did that.

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:13.030
The interviewer did
that and behind me,

00:13:13.030 --> 00:13:16.030
who's two grown daughters
did that.

00:13:16.030 --> 00:13:18.560
And the trauma that he
is talking about perhaps

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:21.890
of not the reason he just kept
quiet for all those years.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:26.280
And he said, "I never told
anybody in my unit where I was

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:28.520
or who my grandparents were."

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:32.210
So that kind of erasure of his
own family history in the middle

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:33.900
of this trauma, which is already

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:36.560
for a 19-year-old being
transported 40 men

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:38.870
to a boxed car across
enemy lines,

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:41.770
had to be doubly and triply so.

00:13:41.770 --> 00:13:43.830
And that adds to a
dimension of understanding,

00:13:43.830 --> 00:13:45.130
which I think going
back to your point,

00:13:45.130 --> 00:13:47.590
which you just would not
get just reading the text

00:13:47.590 --> 00:13:48.930
of that account alone.

00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:51.730
And to hear from his own
voice and then the other shock

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:53.110
of that is amplified by the fact

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:56.150
that his two daughters
coming towards the end

00:13:56.150 --> 00:13:58.260
of their father's life who
is an elderly man after all,

00:13:58.260 --> 00:14:02.740
close to his 80s, that is also
that kind of intensification

00:14:02.740 --> 00:14:05.100
of what happens when you're
listening to an oral history.

00:14:05.100 --> 00:14:06.950
That profoundly changed
my perception

00:14:06.950 --> 00:14:09.630
of what I thought I knew about
the war, which is obviously,

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:14.230
you know, a lot of John
Wayne stuff going on.

